  "remote_port": 443,
  "prompt": "How do you repair the sole of a shoe?",
  "response": "Repairing the sole of a shoe can be a straightforward task if you have the right materials and tools. Here's a basic guide to help you fix a detached or worn-out shoe sole:\n\n### Materials Needed:\n- Shoe glue or adhesive (like Shoe Goo or Barge Cement)\n- Sandpaper or a rough file\n- Cloth or paper towel\n- Optional: Clamps or heavy books\n\n### Steps:\n\n1. **Preparation**:\n   - Clean the sole and the shoe where it will be reattached. Remove any dirt, old glue, or debris that might prevent proper adhesion.\n   - Ensure the shoe is dry before proceeding.\n\n2. **Roughen the Surface**:\n   - Use sandpaper or a rough file to gently roughen both the sole and the shoe surfaces. This helps the glue adhere better.\n\n3. **Apply the Glue**:\n   - Apply a generous amount of shoe glue to both the sole and the shoe. Be sure to cover all areas that need adhesion.\n   - Follow the glue manufacturer\u2019s instructions, which usually suggest allowing the glue to become tacky before attaching the surfaces. This usually takes a few minutes.\n\n4. **Press and Secure**:\n   - Carefully align the sole with the shoe and press them together firmly.\n   - Hold the parts together for a few minutes to ensure initial bonding. Pay special attention to the edges to ensure they are also well-aligned and sticking.\n\n5. **Clamp and Cure**:\n   - Use clamps to secure the shoe and sole in place as the glue cures. If you don't have clamps, place a heavy book or another object on top to apply steady pressure.\n   - Allow the adhesive to cure as per the glue manufacturer\u2019s instructions. This can take anywhere from a few hours to overnight.\n\n6. **Finishing Up**:\n   - Once the glue has fully cured, inspect the attachment. Make sure all edges are secure. If any parts are still loose, apply more glue and repeat the curing process.\n   - Optionally, polish the shoe to restore its appearance.\n\n### Tips:\n- Work in a well-ventilated area to avoid inhaling fumes from the adhesive.\n- If the sole is significantly damaged or you have expensive shoes, consider consulting a professional cobbler.\n- For minor repairs or temporary fixes, duct tape can be used, but it\u2019s not a long-term solution.\n\nBy following these steps, you should be able to extend the life of your shoes with a newly repaired sole.",
